{
  "texts": [
    "An overview of personal home robots is available in [131].",
    "(a) NAO (b) QT (c) Probo (d) Paro (e) Sphero (a) Zenbo [128] (b) Buddy [129] (c) Care-O-bot 4 [130]Fig. 4 Commercial socially-assistive robots in domestic environments [128][129][130] Robots are normally limited by their onboard functionality and hardware.",
    "However, they have the ability to leverage information from other technologies in their environment to perform more complex tasks and requests [108].",
    "For example, a smart environment can be used to locate a patient when the robot is called for support, enhancing navigation skills [132].",
    "A similar approach can be used to find misplaced items for the elderly [133].SARs are also being trialled for use as concierges or receptionists answering questions, checking appointments, assigning patients to medical staff and delivering information and public health education [134][135][136]."
  ]
}